Here's TUnit's lifecycle at each scope:

## 1. Before/After Every Test in a Class

```csharp
public class OrderTests
{
    [Before(Test)]
    public async Task ResetDatabase(TestContext context)
    {
        await InMemoryDb.ResetAsync();
    }

    [After(Test)]
    public async Task Cleanup(TestContext context)
    {
        // runs after each test
    }

    [Test]
    public async Task Order_IsValid() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## 2. Once Before First / After Last Test in a Class

```csharp
public class OrderTests
{
    [Before(Class)]
    public static async Task OpenFixture(ClassHookContext context)
    {
        // runs once before the first test in this class
    }

    [After(Class)]
    public static async Task DisposeFixture(ClassHookContext context)
    {
        // runs once after the last test in this class
    }

    [Test]
    public async Task Order_IsValid() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## 3. Once Per Assembly (all tests in the project)

```csharp
public class WireMockSetup
{
    [Before(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StartServer(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        // start WireMock
    }

    [After(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StopServer(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        // stop WireMock
    }
}
```

## 4. Once Per Entire Test Session (global)

```csharp
public class GlobalDatabaseSetup
{
    [Before(TestSession)]
    public static async Task Migrate(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        // apply EF Core migrations
    }

    [After(TestSession)]
    public static async Task TearDown(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        // drop database
    }
}
```

---

**Key points:**

| Scope | Attribute | Method must be |
|-------|-----------|----------------|
| Each test | `[Before(Test)]` / `[After(Test)]` | Instance |
| Class | `[Before(Class)]` / `[After(Class)]` | **static** |
| Assembly | `[Before(Assembly)]` / `[After(Assembly)]` | **static** |
| Session | `[Before(TestSession)]` / `[After(TestSession)]` | **static** |

There are also `[BeforeEvery(...)]` / `[AfterEvery(...)]` variants that act as **global** cross-cutting hooks (e.g., `[BeforeEvery(Test)]` runs before *every* test in the entire run, not just tests in the declaring class). All hooks can optionally accept a `CancellationToken` parameter.
